WEBVTT

00:02.136 --> 00:06.307
****

00:13.914 --> 00:18.419
****

00:18.552 --> 00:21.655
I couldn't sleep.

00:21.789 --> 00:24.125
We should start taking
your blood pressure every day.

00:26.527 --> 00:29.463
This is very sweet
and responsible.

00:29.597 --> 00:34.001
Yes, I am going to try
to be extra responsible now.

00:34.135 --> 00:35.469
Yeah.

00:38.339 --> 00:42.476
W-We -- We have to talk
about what we...want to do.

00:43.677 --> 00:44.878
I love you.

00:45.012 --> 00:46.214
I want a child.

00:46.347 --> 00:47.815
So I want this child.

00:47.948 --> 00:50.418
I love you, too.

00:50.551 --> 00:53.521
And I do want kids,
but it's complicated.

00:54.822 --> 00:57.057
Is this the right time
in my career?

00:57.191 --> 00:59.193
In our relationship?

00:59.327 --> 01:00.561
Am I too young?

01:00.694 --> 01:01.829
Can we afford this?

01:01.962 --> 01:04.365
Am I willing to make
this commitment right now?

01:04.498 --> 01:06.400
We can start
depositing money

01:06.534 --> 01:08.302
into a shared account
for expenses,

01:08.436 --> 01:10.404
and I can talk to Dr. Glassman
about hiring you an assistant

01:10.538 --> 01:11.605
to help
with your workload --

01:11.739 --> 01:12.906
Shaun, just slow down.

01:13.040 --> 01:15.209
I-I don't need you
to answer these questions now.

01:15.343 --> 01:17.711
I just need to...think.

01:17.845 --> 01:20.013
To figure out what to do.

01:20.148 --> 01:21.882
And you do, too.

01:22.583 --> 01:24.518
****

01:27.321 --> 01:28.889
Dr. Chambers,
I'd like you to meet
a few of our residents.

01:29.022 --> 01:30.124
This is Doctor --
I know that I'm old,

01:30.258 --> 01:32.693
but I can still read
name tags.

01:32.826 --> 01:35.263
Dr. Chambers, you started
experiencing aches

01:35.396 --> 01:37.064
in your right hand
a month ago?

01:37.198 --> 01:39.433
Then tremors, weakness,
spasms.

01:39.567 --> 01:41.735
Had to drop out in the middle
of a bowel resection
last Friday.

01:41.869 --> 01:43.471
I sent you a video
of the surgery.

01:43.604 --> 01:45.072
Given your symptoms, it seems
that carpal tunnel --

01:45.206 --> 01:47.107
Oh, it "seems."

01:47.241 --> 01:49.610
(CHUCKLING)
Well, then, problem solved.

01:50.478 --> 01:51.479
I'll be on my way.

01:51.612 --> 01:53.547
Sir, can I just say
that the documentary

01:53.681 --> 01:55.849
on your work in Haiti
changed my life.

01:55.983 --> 01:57.451
It's the reason
why I went into --

01:57.585 --> 01:59.920
If you want to suck up to me,
call me "doctor," not "sir."

02:00.053 --> 02:01.955
And this is a hospital,
not Coachella.

02:02.089 --> 02:03.557
If you can't wear
something appropriate,

02:03.691 --> 02:05.893
at least try something
that fits.

02:06.026 --> 02:08.128
(SIGHS)

02:08.262 --> 02:10.298
(PAPER RUSTLES)

02:10.431 --> 02:13.066
Rule out autoimmune disorders,
hypothyroidism,

02:13.201 --> 02:16.404
diabetes, amyloidosis, MS,
and multiple myeloma.

02:16.537 --> 02:18.606
Then we'll get back
to carpal tunnel.

02:20.474 --> 02:21.809
Alright.

02:21.942 --> 02:23.143
If you have
any other questions
or concerns,

02:23.277 --> 02:24.245
please don't hesitate --

02:24.378 --> 02:25.613
Twelve.

02:25.746 --> 02:29.217
First, I prefer blankets
not made of sandpaper.

02:29.350 --> 02:31.585
Second,
dim these damn lights.

02:31.719 --> 02:34.422
This isn't some
San Fernando Valley
porn shoot.

02:34.555 --> 02:35.756
Third --
SHAUN: If you made a list,

02:35.889 --> 02:37.291
you don't need
to tell us.

02:41.094 --> 02:43.297
He's had the pain
for nine months now.

02:43.431 --> 02:44.432
ASHER:
And it's on both sides?

02:44.565 --> 02:46.434
Mm-hmm.
Sometimes his forehead,

02:46.567 --> 02:48.001
other times his cheeks,
his nose.

02:48.135 --> 02:50.638
And it's persisting through
very high doses
of hydrocodone.

02:50.771 --> 02:51.972
Yeah, obviously,
the drugs don't work.

02:52.105 --> 02:53.106
It's why I'm here.

02:53.241 --> 02:54.475
ANA: Oscar.

02:54.608 --> 02:56.109
It's a fair question.

02:57.010 --> 02:58.679
Look, I'm sorry.

02:58.812 --> 03:01.048
Okay, I've been
to six doctors now.

03:01.181 --> 03:02.816
I can't work.

03:02.950 --> 03:05.319
I mean, I-I c--
I can't even kiss my wife.

03:05.453 --> 03:06.554
I can hardly smile.

03:06.687 --> 03:08.489
I'm just gonna lightly brush
your cheek.

03:11.625 --> 03:12.560
(GROANS)

03:12.693 --> 03:14.194
Okay.

03:14.328 --> 03:16.129
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

03:16.264 --> 03:18.632
Please...help me.

03:18.766 --> 03:23.036
****

03:23.170 --> 03:24.238
I've been on the phone
for like an hour

03:24.372 --> 03:25.205
with the cable company --

03:25.339 --> 03:26.674
Lea's pregnant.

03:35.483 --> 03:36.650
You want to have...

03:37.150 --> 03:38.786
Yes.

03:38.919 --> 03:39.987
Wow.

03:40.120 --> 03:42.055
(CHUCKLES)

03:42.189 --> 03:43.491
I'm glad you're happy.

03:43.624 --> 03:46.327
Um, do you have
any concerns?

03:46.460 --> 03:48.161
Yes.

03:48.296 --> 03:49.863
Sleep deprivation.

03:49.997 --> 03:52.866
But I have started
looking into
an affordable night nurse.

03:53.000 --> 03:56.604
Well, there's gonna be
some bigger issues.

03:56.737 --> 03:58.339
I mean, this is a...

03:58.472 --> 03:59.873
(LAUGHS)

04:00.007 --> 04:03.511
This is a gigantic moment
for anyone,

04:03.644 --> 04:06.213
especially --
especially for you.

04:06.347 --> 04:08.349
You mean

04:08.482 --> 04:09.683
because of my ASD?

04:09.817 --> 04:10.884
Yeah,
because of your ASD.

04:11.018 --> 04:12.553
Because of your family.

04:15.088 --> 04:16.390
Your job.

04:16.524 --> 04:18.025
I mean...
(CHUCKLES)

04:18.158 --> 04:20.227
A million things.

04:20.361 --> 04:22.463
I don't want to tell you
what -- what to --

04:22.596 --> 04:23.697
I mean, I don't even know
what I...

04:27.401 --> 04:28.902
Having a child

04:31.104 --> 04:33.574
changes everything.

04:33.707 --> 04:35.943
****

04:44.585 --> 04:48.722
****

04:48.856 --> 04:52.526
(WHIRRING)

04:52.660 --> 04:54.428
ASHER:
Nasal cavity's clear.

04:54.562 --> 04:58.298
There's no abscess,
facial tumor, or sinusitis.

04:58.432 --> 05:00.434
It could be
acoustic neuroma.

05:00.568 --> 05:01.902
Without
any hearing loss?

05:02.035 --> 05:03.337
Let's do an MRI
to check.

05:03.471 --> 05:04.304
We've run eight negative tests
already.

05:04.438 --> 05:05.973
We don't need a ninth.

05:06.106 --> 05:07.240
We do the tests
till we know what he has.

05:07.375 --> 05:09.109
It's fibromyalgia.

05:09.242 --> 05:10.744
So, your diagnosis
for his pain

05:10.878 --> 05:12.780
is "pain that no one
can explain"?

05:12.913 --> 05:15.383
Well done.
Some pain's unavoidable.

05:15.516 --> 05:16.884
When I was competing
in Tae Kwon Do,

05:17.017 --> 05:19.286
they taught us to adjust
our relationship to it,

05:19.420 --> 05:20.454
learn to tolerate it.

05:20.588 --> 05:21.722
It can make you stronger.

05:21.855 --> 05:24.091
Wow. That statement has
the absolute ideal ratio

05:24.224 --> 05:25.926
of heartlessness,
humble-bragging, and machismo.

05:26.059 --> 05:27.094
Bravo.

05:27.227 --> 05:29.497
Seriously?
You're pleased with that?

05:29.630 --> 05:31.131
"Machismo," Spanish,
"bravo"'s Italian.

05:31.264 --> 05:32.833
And "humble-bragging"'s 2011.

05:32.966 --> 05:35.335
We can do better,
don't you think?

05:35.469 --> 05:39.306
Maybe we're not
finding anything
because it's psychological?

05:39.440 --> 05:41.942
Some kind of
conversion disorder?

05:43.577 --> 05:44.645
You do the MRI.

05:44.778 --> 05:45.746
I'll talk to the wife.

05:46.146 --> 05:47.648
****

05:47.781 --> 05:50.050
Negative
for endocrine issues.

05:51.719 --> 05:53.554
He's got a history
of moderate carotid stenosis.

05:53.687 --> 05:55.155
If enough plaque
builds up,

05:55.288 --> 05:56.490
starves the brain
of oxygen,

05:56.624 --> 05:58.125
maybe could cause
the hand problems.

05:58.258 --> 06:00.794
If it got that bad,
we'd have already
seen signs of a stroke.

06:00.928 --> 06:02.195
ENRIQUE: Anyone else annoyed
that we're wasting

06:02.329 --> 06:04.965
all these resources to confirm
what's clearly carpal tunnel?

06:05.098 --> 06:07.601
He may be a jerk,
but he's a great doctor.

06:07.735 --> 06:09.069
If Silas Chambers has
a medical opinion,

06:09.202 --> 06:10.438
we better check it out.

06:10.571 --> 06:11.805
I didn't think
he was a jerk.

06:14.942 --> 06:17.645
Dr. Andrews and Dr. Lim
also criticize us

06:17.778 --> 06:19.513
and have
particular demands.

06:19.647 --> 06:21.449
Yeah.
They want us to improve.

06:21.582 --> 06:23.884
How do you know
Dr. Chambers doesn't?

06:24.017 --> 06:25.385
He did improve Enrique.

06:26.954 --> 06:28.188
Not kidding.

06:28.321 --> 06:29.990
You look snazzy.

06:30.123 --> 06:32.826
****

06:36.530 --> 06:39.032
I know
what Dr. Chambers has.

06:39.166 --> 06:41.535
We're having trouble finding
a physical basis

06:41.669 --> 06:42.470
for your husband's pain.

06:45.305 --> 06:46.574
And you defended me
when I asked him

06:46.707 --> 06:48.542
about painkillers earlier.

06:55.983 --> 07:00.053
A few years ago,
Oscar was on a job site.

07:00.187 --> 07:01.655
Working crazy hours.

07:01.789 --> 07:03.356
He was exhausted.

07:04.625 --> 07:06.594
He shot himself with a --
with a nail gun.

07:06.727 --> 07:08.128
Right through his palm.

07:09.362 --> 07:10.898
We didn't have insurance,

07:11.031 --> 07:15.035
so we went to this clinic,
and, um...

07:15.168 --> 07:16.870
Opioids?

07:18.338 --> 07:19.940
Really bad.

07:20.073 --> 07:22.576
Took a year
for him to kick.

07:24.211 --> 07:28.716
Now, um...he's taking
more pills than ever.

07:30.217 --> 07:33.253
Whenever I talk to him
about getting help,

07:33.386 --> 07:35.255
he just gets mad.

07:35.388 --> 07:37.891
I, uh...

07:38.025 --> 07:40.460
I had to move out
last week.

07:42.062 --> 07:43.897
I'm only here
because he asked me to.

07:47.601 --> 07:49.503
I think he's faking.

07:51.572 --> 07:53.106
(SIGHS)

07:53.240 --> 07:57.177
You threw 113 sutures
in your last day of surgery.

07:57.310 --> 08:00.681
In at least half, I detected
a very subtle tremor.

08:00.814 --> 08:04.251
Congratulations on discovering
a symptom I told you about.

08:04.384 --> 08:06.186
It occurs during the part
of your stitch

08:06.319 --> 08:08.822
when the wrist is straight,
not when it's bent.

08:08.956 --> 08:10.558
That is not carpal tunnel.

08:10.691 --> 08:12.626
It is musician's dystonia.

08:12.760 --> 08:14.928
My wrist flexes
on every suture.

08:15.062 --> 08:16.997
You're talking about
a difference of milliseconds.

08:17.130 --> 08:18.766
Yes, he is.

08:18.899 --> 08:20.500
Your condition
was probably caused

08:20.634 --> 08:22.102
by your repetitive technique.

08:22.235 --> 08:25.072
Even Dr. Andrews
throws sutures
in varied ways.

08:25.205 --> 08:26.840
You never do.
This kind of
obsessive behavior

08:26.974 --> 08:29.042
is common
for those with autism.

08:29.176 --> 08:30.277
So, I can refer --

08:30.410 --> 08:31.344
What did you just say?

08:34.615 --> 08:35.783
I'm not autistic.

08:43.490 --> 08:45.893
ANDREWS: Dr. Murphy
didn't mean any offense.

08:46.026 --> 08:47.828
He himself
is on the spectrum.

08:47.961 --> 08:49.462
Oh, is he?

08:49.597 --> 08:52.232
I thought his robotic voice
and hand clasping

08:52.365 --> 08:54.234
were just
charming affectations.

08:54.367 --> 08:57.337
Do you really think
I am anything like him?

08:57.470 --> 08:58.305
I'm not saying that --

08:58.438 --> 08:59.740
I am.

08:59.873 --> 09:01.474
You're extremely organized.

09:01.609 --> 09:03.110
You hardly make eye contact.

09:03.243 --> 09:05.312
And given your problems
with food, blankets,

09:05.445 --> 09:07.915
and lighting, plus the fact
you wear headphones
even in surgery,

09:08.048 --> 09:09.516
you clearly have
sensory issues.

09:09.650 --> 09:11.719
I'm organized.

09:11.852 --> 09:14.054
Would you rather I show up
in the O.R. and just wing it?

09:14.187 --> 09:15.555
I have good taste
in food and music.

09:15.689 --> 09:17.224
Now that's
a mental disorder?

09:18.225 --> 09:19.993
And as
for eye contact...

09:22.630 --> 09:24.497
Okay.

09:24.632 --> 09:26.499
I didn't come here
for a psych consult.

09:26.634 --> 09:29.970
It was just an observation
about a possible reason

09:30.103 --> 09:32.105
for the behavior that led
to your hand symptoms,

09:32.239 --> 09:34.241
which is what we should
be talking about.

09:34.374 --> 09:37.177
Physical therapy is
the recommended course
for dystonia.

09:37.310 --> 09:40.013
I'm not wasting months
on a treatment
that won't work.

09:40.147 --> 09:42.182
I want an MRI-guided
ultrasound ablation

09:42.315 --> 09:44.217
of the VO nucleus
of the thalamus.

09:48.421 --> 09:49.890
You want to jump
to brain surgery?

09:50.023 --> 09:52.192
I would jump
right to amputating a toe

09:52.325 --> 09:54.227
if it got me
my career back.

10:00.734 --> 10:02.803
ANDREWS:
What were you thinking?

10:02.936 --> 10:04.772
You just supported me.

10:04.905 --> 10:07.574
Yes, because part of my job
is not yelling at residents

10:07.708 --> 10:09.209
in front of patients.

10:09.342 --> 10:11.879
What you did is equivalent
to looking at a fuzzy MRI

10:12.012 --> 10:13.580
and blurting out
a patient has cancer.

10:13.714 --> 10:15.215
Cancer can kill you.

10:17.584 --> 10:21.054
Neither diagnosis is one
a patient is excited to hear.

10:22.923 --> 10:24.792
Prep him
for the ablation.

10:24.925 --> 10:27.427
And do not talk to him again
about autism.

10:27.560 --> 10:30.530
****

10:34.134 --> 10:35.969
He's seen six doctors
in the last month,

10:36.103 --> 10:37.370
gotten three
opioid prescriptions,

10:37.504 --> 10:39.239
and he had
a previous opioid problem.

10:39.372 --> 10:40.974
It's textbook
drug-seeking.

10:41.108 --> 10:43.110
It's also textbook
"a bunch of dingbats

10:43.243 --> 10:45.045
missing a trigeminal neuralgia
diagnosis."

10:45.178 --> 10:46.914
Mm, his wife agrees with me.
She knows him.

10:47.047 --> 10:48.481
Would explain why yours
left you.

10:48.615 --> 10:51.118
Snap. Except my wife
didn't leave me,

10:51.251 --> 10:53.253
so neither a good point,
nor even a clever one.

10:53.386 --> 10:55.455
FIESTA imaging would
take hours to set up,

10:55.588 --> 10:56.656
cost the patient
serious money,

10:56.790 --> 10:58.091
and still come out
negative.

10:58.225 --> 11:00.660
Because...it's
textbook drug-seeking.

11:02.029 --> 11:03.997
We have other patients
who need us.

11:04.131 --> 11:05.665
I'm sending
the discharge order.

11:05.799 --> 11:08.101
****

11:12.439 --> 11:14.641
Hey.

11:14.775 --> 11:18.111
(LEA RETCHING)

11:22.615 --> 11:24.184
I hate poop.

11:25.552 --> 11:28.722
Like, what if I suck
at changing diapers?

11:28.856 --> 11:31.124
Maybe we should start
with the bigger issues

11:31.258 --> 11:32.993
and work our way down.

11:35.095 --> 11:36.730
This isn't
at the top of my list,

11:36.864 --> 11:38.298
but since
you are a doctor...

11:39.967 --> 11:41.601
Shaun's ASD --
is it...?

11:41.735 --> 11:43.136
Inheritable?

11:45.172 --> 11:46.774
Probably.

11:46.907 --> 11:48.441
But it's unclear
how much.

11:49.342 --> 11:50.710
So, even that.

11:50.844 --> 11:52.813
W-What am I supposed to do
with that?

11:52.946 --> 11:54.514
Think it through.

11:54.647 --> 11:57.951
Let's say you have
a little baby Shaun.

12:00.821 --> 12:04.157
Like...tiny, honest,

12:05.192 --> 12:08.361
brilliant guy
who adores me...

12:08.495 --> 12:10.964
Mini button-down,

12:11.965 --> 12:13.200
teeny blue eyes...

12:16.669 --> 12:19.172
And me?

12:21.308 --> 12:23.676
A mom?

12:23.811 --> 12:25.745
I mean, I'm not saying
my life would be worse,

12:25.879 --> 12:27.147
but it would just be
so different

12:27.280 --> 12:28.816
from what I was planning.

12:28.949 --> 12:30.517
Not that
I was really planning,

12:30.650 --> 12:35.388
but I am enjoying
just...being.

12:36.857 --> 12:39.026
And so what if you wait?

12:39.159 --> 12:41.561
I just want to make sure
I'm making the right decision.

12:41.694 --> 12:43.196
Mm-hmm.

12:44.064 --> 12:46.599
(SIGHS)

12:48.268 --> 12:50.270
I guess
you'll never really know.

12:52.705 --> 12:56.243
I had to make a lot
of hard choices about my mom.

12:57.510 --> 12:59.847
And I still wake up
wondering

12:59.980 --> 13:01.381
which of them went
the wrong way.

13:03.750 --> 13:07.888
But...you still
gotta choose.

13:08.021 --> 13:11.624
****

13:15.863 --> 13:18.231
(WHIRRING)

13:21.268 --> 13:22.936
No abnormal signal
in the mid pons.

13:24.972 --> 13:26.974
So, are you and Dr. Park
like this at home, too?

13:27.107 --> 13:29.776
When I let him out
of his cage for meals, yes.

13:29.910 --> 13:30.710
(DOOR OPENS)

13:30.844 --> 13:32.412
Hey, we're almost --

13:33.646 --> 13:34.481
(SIGHS)

13:36.383 --> 13:37.484
Oh, come on.

13:37.617 --> 13:39.652
Did you not get the text
I didn't send about this?

13:39.786 --> 13:41.188
Don't bother asking
for consults
if you're gonna --

13:41.321 --> 13:42.956
Wait.

13:43.090 --> 13:45.292
What's that on the right
superior cerebellar artery?

13:46.559 --> 13:49.696
****

13:52.365 --> 13:54.567
An abnormal loop
causing compression.

13:54.701 --> 13:56.870
He has
trigeminal neuralgia.

13:57.004 --> 13:58.371
The pain's real.

13:58.505 --> 14:00.307
****

14:01.408 --> 14:02.842
CLAIRE: We have
good visualization

14:02.976 --> 14:04.711
of the target area.

14:04.844 --> 14:07.347
ANDREWS: Connect
the ultrasound
to the stereotactic frame.

14:07.480 --> 14:11.851
****

14:19.426 --> 14:24.364
****

14:24.497 --> 14:25.765
SHAUN: Ablation won't work.

14:27.134 --> 14:28.468
ENRIQUE:
You changed your mind?

14:28.601 --> 14:29.869
You don't think
he has dystonia?

14:30.003 --> 14:32.339
He does,
but it's a symptom.

14:32.472 --> 14:36.476
His vertebral artery takes
an aberrant course.

14:36.609 --> 14:39.046
It is pressing against
his spinal cord.

14:39.179 --> 14:40.713
He needs vascular surgery
or he'll die.

14:44.017 --> 14:46.019
It's a disorder of the nerve
that carries sensation

14:46.153 --> 14:47.820
from the face
to the brain.

14:47.955 --> 14:50.490
And it's one of
the most painful conditions
that exists.

14:50.623 --> 14:52.325
And very hard
to diagnose.

14:52.459 --> 14:55.162
Thank God Dr. Park approved
all those tests.

14:56.329 --> 14:57.897
(SIGHS)

14:58.031 --> 15:00.667
Y-You were in agony.

15:00.800 --> 15:02.335
And I...

15:05.005 --> 15:07.040
I told him
I thought you were lying.

15:10.643 --> 15:12.745
You thought I was lying?

15:15.848 --> 15:18.351
You thought
I was just being an addict.

15:21.854 --> 15:23.356
And still
you came here with me.

15:26.026 --> 15:27.660
Sat at my side.

15:31.698 --> 15:34.334
We'd like to do
a microvascular decompression.

15:34.467 --> 15:36.203
We'd go in through the back
of your skull

15:36.336 --> 15:39.872
and put in a Teflon patch
to cushion the affected nerve.

15:40.007 --> 15:41.708
You're -- You're cutting
into his brain?

15:41.841 --> 15:43.676
It's relatively safe.
And other options

15:43.810 --> 15:45.912
are unlikely to relieve
the pain.

15:46.046 --> 15:49.116
Look, I-I'll do it.

15:49.249 --> 15:51.251
Uh, thank you so much.

15:53.086 --> 15:55.722
CLAIRE: We want to run
a vertebral artery BTO.

15:55.855 --> 15:57.590
If you tolerate it,
then we would sacrifice the --

15:57.724 --> 15:59.993
Sacrifice the vessel
with onyx embolization.

16:00.127 --> 16:02.129
We recognize you might
not love this proposal.

16:02.262 --> 16:04.131
The one in which
my hand weakness remains,

16:04.264 --> 16:05.465
destroying my career?

16:07.767 --> 16:10.137
Did you consider
vertebral-to-vertebral
artery bypass

16:10.270 --> 16:12.539
with physical removal
of the aberrant artery?

16:12.672 --> 16:16.576
Mm, that would carry
a very high risk
for a stroke or bleed.

16:16.709 --> 16:19.812
It would fix the dystonia
and let me get back to work.

16:19.946 --> 16:22.415
With your history
of carotid stenosis,

16:22.549 --> 16:24.517
it would be a coin flip
whether you survive.

16:24.651 --> 16:26.419
I can live
with those numbers.

16:26.553 --> 16:28.721
Or, for that matter,
die with them.

16:28.855 --> 16:32.825
****

16:32.959 --> 16:36.163
LIM: Corridor
to the trigeminal nerve origin
is open.

16:36.296 --> 16:37.497
PARK: I freed up
the offending vessel.

16:37.630 --> 16:38.598
Teflon sponge.

16:40.300 --> 16:41.501
The sponge is too big.

16:41.634 --> 16:42.669
It'll compress
the brain stem.

16:42.802 --> 16:44.204
I have at least 4 millimeters
of room.

16:44.337 --> 16:45.638
You have half that.

16:45.772 --> 16:47.440
Yes, you have a better view
50 feet away.

16:47.574 --> 16:48.808
LIM: How long have they been
like this?

16:48.941 --> 16:50.810
ASHER: A while.
It's getting worse, though.

16:50.943 --> 16:52.179
MORGAN: Sorry, Park,
you're right.

16:52.312 --> 16:53.180
Just like you were
when you decided

16:53.313 --> 16:55.014
to discharge the sick guy.

16:55.148 --> 16:56.716
Wow,
you invented sarcasm.

16:56.849 --> 16:57.850
Really impressive.

16:57.984 --> 16:59.452
Hey, look at me,
I'm using it, too.

16:59.586 --> 17:01.788
LIM: Park,
you missed the diagnosis.

17:01.921 --> 17:03.956
Reznick,
you ignored protocol.

17:04.091 --> 17:06.326
How about you both show
some humility and shut up?

17:06.459 --> 17:07.760
Sorry.

17:08.928 --> 17:10.830
Teflon's placed.

17:10.963 --> 17:12.465
What if we used the saphenous
vein for the bypass?

17:12.599 --> 17:14.301
Not enough flow.
He'll stroke out.

17:14.434 --> 17:16.069
Carotid
to distal vert, then?

17:16.203 --> 17:17.937
Stenosis is too severe.

17:18.071 --> 17:19.839
Dude's loaded.

17:19.972 --> 17:21.441
He's at retirement age.

17:21.574 --> 17:24.444
He could teach, travel,
screw around all day.

17:24.577 --> 17:27.514
Why is he demanding
that we do this?

17:27.647 --> 17:28.415
When you dedicate your life
to something

17:28.548 --> 17:30.350
that gives you meaning,

17:30.483 --> 17:32.585
it starts to define you.

17:32.719 --> 17:35.388
His decision
may be irrational,
but I get it.

17:35.522 --> 17:36.989
I don't think
it is irrational.

17:38.958 --> 17:42.229
Dr. Chambers has no friends,
no children,

17:42.362 --> 17:43.896
no family,
no outside interests.

17:44.030 --> 17:46.533
If he can't be a surgeon,
he'll have nothing.

17:49.836 --> 17:51.871
I think our best bet
is a radial graft.

17:52.004 --> 17:53.373
Highest flow
I can think of.

17:54.441 --> 17:55.508
Any other ideas?

17:56.543 --> 17:58.878
Okay.
We go with the radial graft.

17:59.011 --> 18:01.013
****

18:06.653 --> 18:08.087
I'm impressed.

18:08.221 --> 18:11.691
I was actually starting
to wonder
if I was losing my touch.

18:11.824 --> 18:13.626
But then I had
a dark afternoon of the soul

18:13.760 --> 18:15.462
and suddenly I knew it

18:15.595 --> 18:17.297
those were
totally solid burns.

18:17.430 --> 18:21.934
Maybe not A+,
but A-, B+ at the worst.

18:22.068 --> 18:25.272
So it hit me -- your plan was
to throw me off my game,

18:25.405 --> 18:26.506
make me doubt myself --

18:26.639 --> 18:27.707
I'm attracted to you.

18:30.243 --> 18:32.145
I've been fighting
this stupid feeling,

18:32.279 --> 18:36.416
trying to find reasons
to not...feel.

18:37.016 --> 18:43.089
****

18:43.223 --> 18:44.824
Are you kidding me?

18:44.957 --> 18:48.795
****

18:51.398 --> 18:53.300
(CHUCKLES) Yes.

18:53.433 --> 18:54.734
Your jokes were lame.

18:54.867 --> 18:56.569
And that's how
you screw with someone.

18:57.904 --> 18:59.239
No.

19:00.273 --> 19:01.974
You're not
that good of a liar.

19:04.211 --> 19:06.513
I-I can't have a roommate
who has feelings for me.

19:06.646 --> 19:08.114
Since when
can't you take a joke?

19:08.248 --> 19:09.582
Since my roommate
hit on me.

19:12.419 --> 19:13.786
You have to move out.

19:14.521 --> 19:16.155
As soon as possible.

19:16.289 --> 19:21.761
****

19:28.735 --> 19:31.003
We've decided to use your
radial artery for the graft.

19:31.137 --> 19:32.772
We've scheduled an O.R.
for tomorrow morning.

19:32.905 --> 19:34.841
Good call.
I agree.

19:34.974 --> 19:36.609
You should risk your life
for this surgery.

19:38.278 --> 19:39.979
Are you being facetious?

19:40.112 --> 19:41.481
No.

19:41.614 --> 19:43.683
(SIGHS)

19:43.816 --> 19:46.986
It just boggles
the mind.

19:47.119 --> 19:48.888
You can't understand
what anyone means.

19:49.021 --> 19:51.558
You can't express yourself
like an adult.

19:51.691 --> 19:54.026
You're a child
playing dress-up.

19:54.160 --> 19:55.928
And everyone here
just plays along.

19:56.062 --> 19:57.330
Let's go, Shaun.

19:57.464 --> 19:58.631
Y-You're agitated.

19:58.765 --> 20:00.633
I'm fine.

20:00.767 --> 20:02.869
You are rubbing your mug.

20:03.002 --> 20:06.205
People with ASD
often have comfort objects

20:06.339 --> 20:07.540
for when
they become agitated.

20:07.674 --> 20:09.642
I can order you
propranolol.

20:10.743 --> 20:12.545
You're gonna give me
the Ruseckas-Freedman

20:12.679 --> 20:14.180
ASD Diagnostic
Questionnaire,

20:14.314 --> 20:16.349
and that's gonna shut
your damn mouth.

20:16.483 --> 20:18.217
Okay, the "Rafad-Q"
is just a tool.

20:18.351 --> 20:21.187
An official diagnosis needs
to come from a psychiatrist.

20:21.321 --> 20:22.655
Well, since I might be dead
tomorrow,

20:22.789 --> 20:24.657
this is
your next-best option.

20:29.362 --> 20:31.564
I'll get the test.

20:36.135 --> 20:37.870
Why can't you treat people
with just an ounce of respect?

20:38.004 --> 20:41.308
Respect has to be earned,
not doled out like candy.

20:41.441 --> 20:43.209
No, that's just an excuse
people like you use

20:43.343 --> 20:44.577
to justify
your garbage behavior.

20:44.711 --> 20:46.245
That's just an excuse people
like you use

20:46.379 --> 20:48.615
to avoid facing reality.

20:48.748 --> 20:51.618
No one was respectful to me
when I was a resident.

20:51.751 --> 20:54.887
They were dismissive
and cruel.

20:55.021 --> 20:57.924
But it lit a fire
and it made me
the man I am today.

20:58.057 --> 21:00.760
The man that you came
into my room idolizing.

21:01.828 --> 21:03.095
Not anymore.

21:03.229 --> 21:04.531
I'm devastated.

21:07.434 --> 21:09.402
Surgeons deal
in human lives,

21:09.536 --> 21:11.237
not childish fantasies.

21:11.371 --> 21:13.205
If you want to succeed,

21:13.340 --> 21:16.075
you're gonna have to be
a lot more like me.

21:17.710 --> 21:23.550
****

21:28.254 --> 21:29.456
Everything okay?

21:29.589 --> 21:31.391
Yep.
Surgery went very smoothly.

21:32.024 --> 21:33.693
No pain right now.

21:33.826 --> 21:35.094
Want to take it
for a test drive?

21:39.366 --> 21:40.333
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

21:47.006 --> 21:48.808
(SHUDDERS)

21:53.380 --> 21:54.647
It's worse.

21:56.949 --> 22:00.052
Collateral circulation
is not ideal.

22:00.186 --> 22:02.655
How are we gonna harvest
the artery?

22:05.458 --> 22:06.626
What's going on?

22:08.995 --> 22:11.831
How much am I gonna
have to change who I am
to be a surgeon?

22:11.964 --> 22:14.333
Ah, to be great --
or even good -- at anything,

22:14.467 --> 22:15.635
we have to compromise.

22:17.236 --> 22:20.407
I used to get too emotionally
involved in my work,

22:20.540 --> 22:22.709
with patients,
everyone.

22:22.842 --> 22:24.844
And I had to learn
to distance myself.

22:24.977 --> 22:27.146
Yeah, you've really grown cold
and heartless.

22:27.279 --> 22:28.448
I have changed.

22:28.581 --> 22:30.683
We all end up changing.

22:30.817 --> 22:32.785
You just got to try
and make it a good change.

22:35.822 --> 22:37.289
I don't want to change.

22:40.660 --> 22:42.795
I want to change
what's around me.

22:46.433 --> 22:48.000
Oh, I'll figure it out.
(CHUCKLES)

22:48.134 --> 22:49.802
I'm sure you will.

22:49.936 --> 22:51.871
Hey, you're the guy who makes
living in a van look cool.

22:52.004 --> 22:54.807
(CHUCKLES)

22:54.941 --> 22:56.409
So, uh, the circulation...

22:56.543 --> 22:59.378
The right side looks like
it has better length.

22:59.512 --> 23:01.948
Yeah.
Better collateral, too.

23:02.081 --> 23:03.983
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

23:07.119 --> 23:08.555
Given the poor outcome,

23:08.688 --> 23:10.923
we can't recommend
further surgery right now.

23:11.057 --> 23:12.992
We suggest six months
of pain medication

23:13.125 --> 23:15.895
and referrals
to neurology and pain
management specialists.

23:17.664 --> 23:19.732
W-What surgery
aren't you recommending?

23:19.866 --> 23:22.001
A DREZ lesioning.

23:22.134 --> 23:23.736
We'd cut the signal
from the trigeminal nerve

23:23.870 --> 23:25.938
to the sensory areas
of your brain.

23:26.072 --> 23:28.608
But there's a real possibility
of paralysis

23:28.741 --> 23:31.177
on one side of your body.

23:31.310 --> 23:32.545
I want the surgery.

23:32.679 --> 23:35.347
ANA: Baby, I'll help you
manage the pain.

23:35.482 --> 23:38.350
I-I'll move back in.

23:38.485 --> 23:40.252
I'll take care of you.

23:40.386 --> 23:42.855
You know
how I treated you before.

23:44.356 --> 23:46.726
I'm only gonna get worse.

23:46.859 --> 23:48.928
I would never
leave you again.

23:50.497 --> 23:52.431
That's what scares me.

23:52.565 --> 23:55.034
I'd start
cutting you down,

23:56.068 --> 23:57.269
being cruel,

23:58.538 --> 23:59.806
and you'd just put up
with it.

23:59.939 --> 24:01.974
(SIGHS)

24:02.108 --> 24:04.376
I won't let that happen.

24:04.511 --> 24:05.945
(CLICKS TONGUE)

24:08.715 --> 24:10.517
We'll prep an O.R.

24:14.253 --> 24:16.756
"I frequently point out
other people's mistakes."

24:16.889 --> 24:17.990
Duh.

24:18.124 --> 24:20.292
That's a yes.

24:20.426 --> 24:22.629
"People tell me
I overthink things."

24:22.762 --> 24:24.764
Only people
who underthink things.

24:24.897 --> 24:26.432
But, fine, another yes.

24:26.566 --> 24:28.835
"I sometimes speak
in an abnormal tone."

24:28.968 --> 24:30.670
Who thinks they speak
in an abnormal tone?

24:30.803 --> 24:32.404
Just mark no.

24:32.539 --> 24:33.840
How many more of these?

24:33.973 --> 24:36.543
None.

24:36.676 --> 24:38.911
Your answers
are fully congruent
with someone on the spectrum.

24:40.412 --> 24:41.413
No.

24:41.548 --> 24:42.849
You keyed it wrong.

24:42.982 --> 24:44.450
No, look. No, I --
Or something.

24:44.584 --> 24:45.918
Here. Look, I didn't.
No, give it to me.

24:46.052 --> 24:47.119
No, I...
Oh! Don't!

24:47.253 --> 24:48.120
(MUG SHATTERS)

24:50.056 --> 24:51.924
You idiot!

24:52.058 --> 24:53.626
S-Stupid, careless --

24:53.760 --> 24:54.827
I-I stepped back --

24:54.961 --> 24:55.995
Get out of my room.

24:57.129 --> 24:58.264
Get out!
Okay.

24:58.397 --> 25:01.601
****

25:01.734 --> 25:05.938
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

25:06.072 --> 25:07.339
LIM: Make sure
we're not impacting

25:07.473 --> 25:08.675
normal spinal cord
pathways.

25:08.808 --> 25:10.242
ASHER: Somatosensories
are at baseline.

25:10.977 --> 25:12.111
PARK: BP's steady.

25:13.479 --> 25:16.148
(ALARM SOUNDING)

25:16.282 --> 25:18.785
Leg and arm SSEPs
at 50% decreased amplitude.

25:18.918 --> 25:20.452
Check the cord above and below
for hematoma

25:20.587 --> 25:21.954
or bony compression.

25:22.088 --> 25:23.322
Cord's fine.

25:23.455 --> 25:25.091
Push IV fluids
and start pressors.

25:25.224 --> 25:26.158
So, what is it?

25:27.459 --> 25:28.961
I don't know.

25:32.799 --> 25:34.901
(ALARM SOUNDING)

25:35.034 --> 25:36.603
LIM: Any issues
with motor potentials?

25:36.736 --> 25:38.504
ASHER: Unilateral amplitude
down 70%.

25:38.638 --> 25:40.472
PARK: We're about to get
total neurological collapse.

25:40.607 --> 25:42.308
MORGAN: It's a clot
from a small branch artery.

25:42.441 --> 25:43.643
We checked
the spinal blood vessels --

25:43.776 --> 25:45.311
The outside.

25:45.444 --> 25:47.346
But the electrode could have
injured a sulcal artery.

25:47.479 --> 25:48.881
We need to follow
the DREZ pathway inward

25:49.015 --> 25:50.316
and search
for a small clot.

25:50.449 --> 25:52.484
Start at the site of last
ablation with the electrode.

25:52.619 --> 25:53.686
It's gotta be deep.

25:55.321 --> 25:56.856
This'll be easier
if she's in here.

25:58.290 --> 26:00.092
Scrub in, Dr. Reznick.

26:00.226 --> 26:02.494
****

26:05.397 --> 26:07.066
CLAIRE: We're setting up
the neuromonitoring

26:07.199 --> 26:08.500
for Silas' surgery.

26:11.938 --> 26:13.205
He's angry with me.

26:13.339 --> 26:14.707
Silas?

26:14.841 --> 26:16.508
He's angry
with everyone.

26:16.643 --> 26:19.411
Dr. Andrews said to stop
talking to him about ASD.

26:19.545 --> 26:21.914
But I brought it up anyway,
gave him a test,

26:22.048 --> 26:25.217
his mug broke,
and I don't know
what to do now.

26:25.351 --> 26:26.518
I don't know what to feel.

26:26.653 --> 26:28.254
And Lea --

26:30.556 --> 26:33.626
Lea told me
about the pregnancy.

26:41.834 --> 26:43.335
Okay.

26:43.469 --> 26:44.904
(EXHALES SHAKILY)

26:48.741 --> 26:49.809
Is this hard for me
because I'm dealing

26:49.942 --> 26:51.644
with both things
at once?

26:54.080 --> 26:56.348
I think both things
are related.

27:00.552 --> 27:02.054
What if my child

27:02.855 --> 27:05.224
has no friends?

27:05.357 --> 27:06.793
What if
they're picked on?

27:06.926 --> 27:08.460
This is not
small-town Wyoming.

27:08.594 --> 27:09.829
The world has changed,
Shaun.

27:09.962 --> 27:12.064
I haven't changed.

27:12.699 --> 27:13.866
How can I...

27:16.502 --> 27:17.737
...know what
they're feeling?

27:17.870 --> 27:19.505
How can I comfort them?

27:22.408 --> 27:24.276
How can I be
a good father?

27:29.348 --> 27:31.217
Remember
when we first met?

27:31.350 --> 27:32.885
Right over there?

27:34.553 --> 27:35.922
You were mad at me.

27:36.055 --> 27:39.291
Yeah. But you were right
about the patient.

27:39.425 --> 27:40.492
And you were stubborn.

27:40.626 --> 27:41.894
And crazy smart.

27:42.028 --> 27:43.996
And you are still
all of those things.

27:45.197 --> 27:49.869
But if you were still
just that guy

27:50.002 --> 27:51.670
that I met
running through those doors,

27:51.804 --> 27:53.773
we would not be sitting here
right now.

27:56.342 --> 27:57.944
You have changed.

27:59.645 --> 28:01.814
You've adapted.
You've grown.

28:03.249 --> 28:04.516
Do you know
how hard that is?

28:04.650 --> 28:06.352
Most people
don't even try.

28:08.988 --> 28:15.027
And you are going to grow
into a great father.

28:15.161 --> 28:17.329
Whenever it happens.

28:17.463 --> 28:23.535
****

28:26.538 --> 28:33.112
****

28:33.245 --> 28:34.981
MORGAN:
Slowly go perpendicular

28:35.114 --> 28:36.682
at the angle
of our ablation electrode.

28:36.816 --> 28:38.150
(ALARM SOUNDING)

28:38.284 --> 28:39.518
Still not seeing
the clot.

28:39.651 --> 28:42.354
ASHER:
Amplitude loss at 80%.

28:42.488 --> 28:43.890
Maybe it's not a clot.

28:44.023 --> 28:45.958
Maybe it's something
higher up,
in the brain.

28:46.092 --> 28:49.128
PARK: No.
You were right the first time.

28:49.261 --> 28:53.165
Maybe it's hiding behind some
ultrasound-impervious segment.

28:54.366 --> 28:56.435
Cut the dentate ligament.

28:56.568 --> 28:59.138
It'll get
more lateral access.

28:59.271 --> 29:00.639
LIM: Completely section
the ligament.

29:00.773 --> 29:04.543
****

29:04.676 --> 29:06.078
I see it.

29:08.915 --> 29:10.549
Removing the clot.

29:10.682 --> 29:14.520
(ALARM STOPS, MONITOR BEEPS)

29:14.653 --> 29:16.889
ASHER: Amplitude returning
to normal baseline.

29:17.023 --> 29:22.761
****

29:22.895 --> 29:24.296
Let me know
if you need me.

29:24.430 --> 29:25.697
LIM: We're good.

29:25.832 --> 29:26.966
Thank you.

29:27.099 --> 29:32.204
****

29:32.839 --> 29:34.106
Hey.

29:35.842 --> 29:37.376
We did good together.

29:37.509 --> 29:38.644
We did.

29:40.712 --> 29:41.647
You still have to move out,
though.

29:41.780 --> 29:43.482
Tonight.

29:43.615 --> 29:47.086
****

29:52.992 --> 29:55.494
On my first day here,
Dr. Melendez said

29:55.627 --> 29:58.430
I would never do anything
besides suction.

29:58.564 --> 30:01.567
But later, he let me make
my first surgical incision.

30:01.700 --> 30:03.735
He became my friend.

30:03.870 --> 30:05.404
I miss him.

30:05.537 --> 30:07.539
Are you
in the right room?

30:07.673 --> 30:11.110
Did somebody tell you
I needed pointless stories?

30:11.243 --> 30:13.779
I used to think

30:13.913 --> 30:17.749
being a doctor was
all I needed to make me happy.

30:19.886 --> 30:21.620
It did make me happy.

30:22.922 --> 30:25.824
But I realized
I wanted more.

30:26.792 --> 30:28.827
And that
I could have more.

30:30.897 --> 30:32.264
I changed.

30:35.301 --> 30:38.404
You can change, too.

30:38.537 --> 30:40.306
But not if you're dead
from this surgery.

30:43.009 --> 30:45.777
I've made up my mind.

30:45.912 --> 30:47.813
Please leave.

30:47.947 --> 30:49.848
My brother Steve,

30:49.982 --> 30:52.851
he gave me a plastic scalpel
before he died.

30:52.985 --> 30:54.653
It broke.
I was very sad.

30:54.786 --> 30:56.222
I asked you to leave.

30:56.355 --> 31:03.062
****

31:03.195 --> 31:06.598
When I fixed my scalpel,
it made me feel better.

31:06.732 --> 31:12.204
****

31:14.941 --> 31:20.479
****

31:20.612 --> 31:24.516
I was 9 years old
when my father died.

31:28.620 --> 31:31.590
I loved drinking hot chocolate
with him in the morning.

31:31.723 --> 31:35.727
He'd bring me a mug
after every business trip.

31:37.329 --> 31:39.865
He understood me.

31:39.999 --> 31:41.133
My mother didn't.

31:41.267 --> 31:43.102
Nobody did.

31:43.235 --> 31:47.106
I tried fitting in,
but...

31:48.674 --> 31:50.509
I got frustrated.

31:50.642 --> 31:52.911
So I gave up.

31:54.013 --> 31:56.048
On relationships.

31:56.182 --> 31:57.683
On friends.

31:57.816 --> 32:01.620
On all but the one thing
I was good at.

32:04.356 --> 32:08.160
And now, Dr. Murphy,
I'm too old.

32:08.294 --> 32:09.861
I've made
too many enemies.

32:09.996 --> 32:11.197
Too many mistakes.

32:12.999 --> 32:18.070
People tolerate me
because I save lives.

32:22.508 --> 32:23.542
Without that

32:25.244 --> 32:28.914
why would anyone ever care
about me?

32:29.048 --> 32:31.583
****

32:33.785 --> 32:35.887
I care.

